transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, and thank you for having me. I'm glad to participate in this interview. Please feel free to ask your questions, and I'll do my best to provide detailed and honest answers.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Certainly! As I mentioned earlier, I’m Aubrey, and I’m 52 years old. I used to be a teacher, but I’ve been retired for a few years now. I live in rural Montana, which I love for its quiet and natural beauty. As a widow, I’ve found ways to keep myself engaged, like volunteering in the local community and staying active through exercise. I’m quite health-conscious and have worked hard to manage my hypertension. I also have two grown children, which keeps me connected to family. Overall, I feel fortunate to have a comfortable lifestyle and good healthcare coverage through Medicare. I try to take care of my health, but I do have some challenges, like managing my weight and dealing with prediabetes and anemia. How about you?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course. I had two pregnancies in my younger years. I remember the first time I found out I was pregnant; I was in my late twenties, and I was both excited and a bit nervous. It was a time of significant change for me. I had just started my teaching career and wasn’t quite sure how I would balance everything. My second pregnancy came a few years later, and by then, I felt more prepared and confident. Both pregnancies were vaginal deliveries, and while I had some challenges, like managing my weight and stress, I tried to stay healthy throughout. 

After my children were born, I focused on being the best mother I could be, but I never planned on having more children after that. I felt that was the right number for me. Looking back, I have fond memories of those times, but I also recognize the toll it took on my body, especially with my current health issues. Would you like to know more about my experiences during those pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care shortly after I found out I was pregnant with my first child. I think it was around the end of my first trimester. I remember feeling a mixture of excitement and anxiety as I entered the clinic for my first appointment. The healthcare provider was very supportive, and they provided a wealth of information about what to expect during pregnancy, which was reassuring. 

During my first pregnancy, I had regular check-ups, and I appreciated the opportunity to ask questions and discuss any concerns I had. They monitored my weight and blood pressure closely, which was important for me, especially since I now know that I have a history of weight management issues. 

For my second pregnancy, I was more familiar with the process, so I felt more at ease going into my appointments. I had a good rapport with my healthcare provider, which made a big difference. I felt comfortable discussing any issues, including my stress levels and how to manage my health better during that time.

Overall, I would say my experiences with prenatal care were positive. However, I do remember sometimes feeling overwhelmed by the information and the responsibilities that came with being a mother. It was essential for me to stay informed, but it could be a lot to process. Do you want to know more about specific challenges I faced during those pregnancies or how I managed my health?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I'm glad to share more about my experiences. Since I’m not currently receiving prenatal care, I can reflect on the providers I had during my pregnancies. Both of my pregnancies were managed by the same healthcare provider, a family doctor who specialized in women's health. 

I had a very positive relationship with my healthcare provider. They were always approachable and took the time to listen to my concerns, which was incredibly comforting. I felt that I could ask any question, no matter how trivial it seemed. They encouraged me to be proactive about my health and provided practical advice on nutrition and exercise, which I tried to incorporate into my routine.

The provider was thorough in their examinations and made sure to monitor my blood pressure and weight closely, especially since I had concerns about gaining too much weight during my pregnancies. I appreciated their emphasis on my overall well-being, not just the physical aspects of pregnancy. They also took the time to discuss mental health, which I found valuable, particularly given the stress of balancing my career and new motherhood.

Even after my pregnancies, I felt comfortable reaching out to them for any follow-up questions or concerns. It’s important to have that kind of relationship with a healthcare provider, as it fosters trust and openness. Would you like to know more about any specific aspects of that relationship or how it may have influenced my overall health?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: During my pregnancies, I had regular prenatal appointments, typically every four weeks during the first trimester, then every two weeks as I got closer to my due date. Each visit was structured, which helped me feel prepared.

A typical appointment would start with checking in with the nurse or medical assistant, who would take my weight and blood pressure. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and anxiety during those moments, especially when they checked my weight, given my concerns about managing it.

After that, I would meet with my healthcare provider. They would ask about how I was feeling, any changes I noticed, and if I had any concerns. I always appreciated that they took the time to listen to me and discuss my experiences. We would discuss my diet and exercise, and they would often provide tips on how to stay active and manage my weight effectively during pregnancy.

They would also conduct a physical examination, including listening to the baby's heartbeat, which was always a highlight for me. It was such a reassuring sound! Depending on where I was in my pregnancy, there might be additional tests, like glucose screening or ultrasound appointments to monitor the baby’s development.

Towards the end of my pregnancies, the visits became more frequent as we prepared for delivery. I felt that each appointment was essential in ensuring that both my health and my baby's health were on track. I left each visit feeling more informed and empowered, which was important to me.

If you're interested, I can share more about the specific tests or discussions we had during those visits or how I felt about the overall process of prenatal care.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I did encounter some health concerns, but thankfully, I wouldn’t classify them as severe complications. In both pregnancies, I struggled with managing my weight, which was a constant source of worry for me. I was aware of my tendency to gain more than what was recommended, and my healthcare provider was diligent about monitoring this. They provided guidance on diet and exercise, which I tried to follow, but it was a challenge.

Additionally, I dealt with some episodes of elevated blood pressure, which was concerning, especially since I have well-controlled hypertension now. My healthcare provider kept a close watch on this, and I was advised to rest more and reduce stress whenever possible. I remember feeling anxious about the potential risks associated with high blood pressure during pregnancy, but my provider was always reassuring and helped me understand what steps we could take to manage it.

I also experienced some anemia during my second pregnancy, which was addressed through dietary changes and supplements. It was a bit disconcerting at times, especially when I felt fatigued, but my provider was proactive in managing it, which helped me feel more at ease.

Overall, while there were challenges, I felt supported throughout the process. I was grateful for the care I received and felt that my healthcare provider's attentiveness made a significant difference in how I managed these issues. If you’d like, I can elaborate on how I coped with these challenges or how they may have impacted my postpartum health.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I'm currently taking a few medications and supplements to manage my health conditions. For my well-controlled hypertension, I take a low-dose medication that helps keep my blood pressure stable. It's been effective, and I've been able to maintain good numbers with it.

In addition to that, I take a supplement for my anemia. My healthcare provider recommended an iron supplement to help boost my levels, as I tend to struggle with fatigue due to the anemia. I also make sure to include iron-rich foods in my diet, such as leafy greens and lean meats, as part of my effort to manage that condition.

I don't take any hormonal contraception at the moment, as I have completed my family planning. However, I used to take hormonal birth control for a number of years, which helped me regulate my menstrual cycle and manage other related symptoms.

I also try to keep a multivitamin on hand to ensure I'm getting a broad range of nutrients, especially since I have some dietary restrictions due to my health concerns.

If you're interested, I can provide more details about how I manage taking these medications or how they fit into my overall health routine.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was quite conscious of my diet and nutrition, knowing how essential it was for both my health and my babies' development. I tried to focus on a balanced diet that included a variety of food groups. I emphasized fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins, as I wanted to ensure I was getting the nutrients needed.

In my first pregnancy, I was initially a bit overwhelmed with all the dietary recommendations, but I was eager to learn. My healthcare provider provided guidance on what to eat and what to avoid, which helped me navigate things better. I made a point to incorporate calcium-rich foods since I wanted to support my baby’s bone development. I also paid attention to getting enough folic acid, which I knew was important for preventing neural tube defects.

However, I struggled with cravings during both pregnancies. I often found myself wanting comfort food, which wasn't always the healthiest choice. I tried to indulge in moderation, but there were times when I gave in to those cravings more than I should have. I remember enjoying things like mashed potatoes and ice cream, which I later learned weren't the best for managing my weight.

During my second pregnancy, I became more aware of my pre-existing issues with weight management and tried to be more disciplined about what I ate. I made a conscious effort to avoid sugary snacks and opted for healthier alternatives. I started meal prepping to help me stick to my nutritional goals, which made a significant difference. I also made sure to stay hydrated by drinking plenty of water, especially as I learned how important hydration was during pregnancy.

Overall, I would say my diet was a work in progress. While I aimed for a healthy balance, I had my moments of struggle, and it was a journey to find what worked best for me. If you'd like, I can share more about specific challenges I faced with my diet or any changes I made as a result of my experiences.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, my emotional experiences were quite varied. I remember initially feeling a whirlwind of emotions, from excitement to anxiety. The anticipation of becoming a mother was thrilling, but it also came with a lot of worries about the changes my body would undergo and how I would handle the responsibilities of motherhood.

In my first pregnancy, I found myself feeling somewhat overwhelmed at times. I was balancing my new teaching career and preparing for a baby, which created a bit of stress. I worried about everything—from my health to how I would manage my time once the baby arrived. However, I tried to stay positive and focused on the joy of bringing new life into the world. Having a supportive healthcare provider helped me navigate those feelings, as they encouraged open discussions about my emotions.

By the time I was pregnant with my second child, I felt more confident and emotionally prepared. I had learned a lot from my first experience, and I was more aware of the importance of taking care of my mental health. I practiced mindfulness and made an effort to stay connected with friends and family, which provided me with a strong support system. I found that talking about my feelings and concerns with others made a significant difference in how I managed any anxiety.

That said, there were still moments when I felt overwhelmed, particularly with the physical changes and the pressure of being a good mother. I had to remind myself that it was okay to seek help and that I didn't have to do everything perfectly. I also made sure to carve out time for myself, whether it was going for a walk or enjoying a quiet moment with a book.

Overall, my emotional journey during pregnancy was a mix of joy and challenges, but I learned a lot about myself and how to manage my feelings. If you're interested, I can elaborate on any specific moments or coping strategies I used during those times.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, my support network was incredibly important to me. I had a variety of people who played significant roles in providing emotional and practical support. 

First and foremost, my family was a tremendous source of support. My parents were always there for me, offering encouragement and advice. They had experienced parenthood themselves, so their wisdom was invaluable. My siblings also provided a great deal of support; they would often check in on me and help out whenever they could. I remember my sister throwing a baby shower for me during my second pregnancy, which was a wonderful way to celebrate and connect with family.

My friends were also a crucial part of my support system. Many of them had children themselves, so they understood what I was going through. We would often share experiences, frustrations, and joys, which helped me feel less isolated. Just having someone to talk to about the ups and downs of pregnancy made a big difference. I remember meeting with a close friend regularly for walks, which helped us both stay active and gave us time to catch up and discuss our lives.

Additionally, I felt supported by my healthcare provider, as I mentioned earlier. Their encouragement and willingness to listen made a significant impact on my emotional well-being. I appreciated their approach to discussing not just my physical health but also my emotional state, which helped me feel more at ease.

Overall, I was fortunate to have a diverse support network that included family, friends, and healthcare professionals. Their presence helped me navigate the emotional rollercoaster of pregnancy. If you’d like, I can share more about specific instances where support made a significant difference or any challenges I faced in seeking help.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I did put thought into my birth plan, though I must admit that my preferences evolved as I gained more experience and knowledge. With my first pregnancy, I approached the idea of a birth plan with excitement but also some uncertainty. I had a general idea of wanting a vaginal delivery, as I had heard that it was beneficial for both mother and baby. I also wanted to have a supportive environment where I felt comfortable and safe.

As I prepared for my first delivery, I expressed my desire to have my partner with me during labor, which was incredibly important. I wanted to have that emotional support by my side. I also hoped for minimal interventions, like avoiding an epidural if possible, although I was open to it if the situation warranted it.

By the time I was pregnant with my second child, I felt more prepared and knowledgeable about the birthing process. I had a clearer vision of what I wanted. I still favored a vaginal delivery, but I was more open to discussing pain management options, including the possibility of an epidural. My experience with the first delivery taught me that being flexible was key, as things don’t always go as planned.

I also considered the importance of a calm and supportive atmosphere during labor. I wanted to ensure that the healthcare team respected my wishes, but I was also aware that I needed to be adaptable to any changes in my health or the baby's well-being. Communication with my healthcare provider was crucial, and I felt fortunate to have a provider who listened to my preferences and included me in the decision-making process.

Overall, my birth plans were a blend of my hopes and a willingness to adapt to the circumstances. If you'd like, I can elaborate on any specific aspects of my birth experiences or how my preferences shifted from one pregnancy to the next.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I made a concerted effort to educate myself about pregnancy and childbirth, as I wanted to feel informed and empowered. I used a variety of sources to gather information, which helped me navigate the experience.

First and foremost, I relied on my healthcare provider. They were an excellent resource, and I appreciated their willingness to answer my questions and provide guidance tailored to my individual circumstances. I made it a point to ask about any topics I was uncertain about during my prenatal visits, which made a significant difference in my understanding.

In addition to my provider, I read several pregnancy books that were recommended to me. One of my favorites was "What to Expect When You're Expecting." It provided a comprehensive overview of each stage of pregnancy and addressed common concerns and questions. I also enjoyed reading books focused on childbirth, which helped me understand the process better and prepare for what to expect during labor.

Online resources were another avenue I explored. I found reputable websites, such as those run by organizations like the American Pregnancy Association and the Mayo Clinic, to be particularly helpful. They provided evidence-based information on various topics, from nutrition and exercise to labor and delivery options. I was cautious about the sources I chose, wanting to ensure they were credible and trustworthy.

I also joined a few online forums and local parenting groups where I could connect with other expectant mothers. Sharing experiences and advice with others in similar situations was incredibly valuable. It helped me realize that I wasn't alone in my feelings and concerns. Hearing from women who had been through the process before me provided me with practical insights and encouragement.

Lastly, I attended a childbirth education class offered by my local hospital. That was an eye-opening experience, as it covered everything from labor stages to pain management options. I found it reassuring to meet other expectant parents and share in the learning experience together.

Overall, I utilized a mix of professional guidance, literature, online resources, and community support to educate myself about pregnancy and childbirth. If you're interested, I can share more about any specific resources or experiences that stood out to me during that time.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, managing the financial aspects was definitely a consideration, though I was fortunate to have a stable income and good healthcare coverage through Medicare. However, I still took proactive steps to ensure that I was prepared for the costs associated with having a baby.

First, I made a budget to account for the various expenses related to pregnancy and preparing for a new baby. This included costs like prenatal care visits, ultrasound appointments, and any necessary tests. I was diligent about keeping track of these expenses to understand what my out-of-pocket costs would be, especially since I was aware that Medicare doesn't cover everything related to pregnancy.

I also researched and planned for the expenses related to childbirth. I looked into what my hospital would charge for the delivery and any potential additional costs, such as anesthesia if I chose to have an epidural. I wanted to avoid any surprises, so I contacted the billing department to get a clearer picture of potential expenses.

In terms of preparing for the baby, I created a list of essential items I would need, such as a crib, car seat, and baby clothes. I tried to be practical and focused on what was absolutely necessary, which helped me manage costs better. I also took advantage of sales and discounts when shopping for baby items, and I was open to accepting gently used items from friends and family, which saved me quite a bit.

I remember being mindful of my spending on maternity clothes as well. I opted for versatile pieces that I could wear throughout my pregnancy and afterward, rather than buying an entirely new wardrobe.

Overall, while there were certainly financial considerations, I felt that my planning and support system helped me navigate those aspects effectively. If you’d like, I can share more about specific financial challenges I faced or strategies I used to manage costs during my pregnancies.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, my work situation was certainly impacted, especially since I was a teacher at the time. When I found out I was pregnant with my first child, I had to navigate the balance between my career and preparing for motherhood. I remember feeling excited but also anxious about how I would manage my responsibilities.

With my first pregnancy, I worked until about a month before my due date. I was fortunate to have supportive colleagues and administration, which made a significant difference. I was open about my pregnancy with my supervisor, and they were understanding when I needed to adjust my workload or take breaks as I got further along. I made an effort to ensure that my students were well-prepared and that my lesson plans were organized for when I would be on maternity leave.

As I approached my delivery date, I was focused on wrapping things up at work. I wanted to ensure a smooth transition for my students and my substitute teacher. I found that the emotional support from my coworkers helped alleviate some of the stress I felt as I prepared for this major life change.

By the time I was pregnant with my second child, I had a better grasp on what to expect regarding both work and motherhood. I had a bit more confidence in managing my time and responsibilities. I also had the benefit of experience, which allowed me to communicate with my employer about my needs more effectively. I decided to take a longer maternity leave for my second child to ensure that I had ample time to bond and recover.

Overall, while my pregnancies changed my work dynamic, I felt fortunate to have a supportive environment that allowed me to navigate those challenges. If you'd like to know more about how I managed my responsibilities or any specific challenges I faced at work during my pregnancies, I’d be happy to share.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I did think quite a bit about the postpartum period and what it would mean for me as a new mother. I understood that the transition to motherhood would come with its own set of challenges and joys, so I tried to prepare myself as best as I could.

For my first pregnancy, I was somewhat naive about the physical and emotional changes I would experience after giving birth. I thought that once the baby arrived, everything would fall into place. However, as I learned more about postpartum recovery, I realized the importance of having a plan in place. I made sure to discuss postpartum care with my healthcare provider during my prenatal visits, which helped me gain a realistic perspective.

I planned to take adequate time off work to recover and bond with my baby. I aimed for at least six weeks of maternity leave, understanding that I would need that time to heal physically and adjust to my new role as a mother. I also wanted to ensure that I had support during this period, especially from family and friends who could help with tasks around the house or provide emotional support.

I was also aware of the potential for postpartum mood disorders, as I had heard that many women experience emotional ups and downs after childbirth. I made it a point to stay connected with my support network, which included my family and friends, to talk openly about my feelings and seek help if needed. I knew that being proactive about my mental health would be crucial.

For my second pregnancy, I felt more prepared and knowledgeable about the postpartum experience. I had a clearer idea of what to expect, and I planned for more help at home. I arranged for a family member to stay with us for a couple of weeks after the birth to provide extra support, which I knew would make a significant difference.

I also focused on self-care as part of my postpartum plan. I aimed to carve out time for myself, whether it was going for short walks or engaging in activities that brought me joy. I recognized the importance of taking care of my physical and mental health to be the best mother I could be.

Overall, while I had my hopes and plans for the postpartum period, I understood the need to be flexible and adaptable to whatever challenges might arise. If you're interested, I can share more about specific aspects of my postpartum plans or any particular concerns I had as I approached that phase.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
